  <Fragment slot="methodology">
    <section>
      <h2 id="how-we-evaluate">How we evaluate</h2>
      <p>For this roundup, we compared each grinder using a practical home-brewer lens instead of spec-sheet theater. The highest weight went to grind consistency in the cup, then adjustment usefulness across brew methods, retention behavior, cleanup burden, and overall long-term value under a hard $200 ceiling. We looked for grinders that improve daily coffee quality without introducing complicated routines most people will abandon.</p>
      <p>We separated espresso-capable and filter-first recommendations because this budget class includes both, and the wrong choice wastes money quickly. A grinder can be excellent for drip and still frustrate espresso users if fine-range adjustment is too coarse. Likewise, an espresso-focused grinder can be overkill for households brewing only batch coffee. That distinction matters more than flashy marketing language.</p>
      <p>Retention and static were treated as workflow-critical, not cosmetic details. When grounds cling to chutes or scatter over the counter, people skip good habits and coffee quality drops over time. A model with slightly lower spec bragging rights but cleaner daily behavior can outperform a “higher tier” grinder in real life because you actually use it consistently.</p>
      <p>We also prioritized maintainability. Accessible burr chambers, straightforward reassembly, and predictable setting return all influence long-term ownership satisfaction. Under $200, reliability and serviceability often beat chasing the absolute highest burr diameter. The goal is not perfection; it is dependable performance that still feels easy six months from now.</p>
      <p>Finally, we grouped recommendations by buyer intent: budget filter upgrade, all-around home use, espresso-first control, and manual value. This helps avoid one-size-fits-all picks and lets you choose based on your actual brew habits instead of generic “best overall” claims.</p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

