  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2>Who should skip this guide?</h2>
      <p>If your budget can stretch to the mid-$300 range, you may get better long-term value from a grinder with larger burrs, lower retention, and easier micro-adjustment for espresso. This under-$200 list is for buyers who need strong value now, not top-end speed or café-level workflow refinement.</p>
      <p>You should also skip this guide if you only need occasional pre-ground coffee support and do not plan to dial recipes at all. In that case, a burr grinder may be unnecessary complexity. But if you care about consistency and want repeatable cups, the picks above are the strongest value options before the next pricing tier.</p>

      <h2>Common mistakes when shopping for a burr grinder under $200</h2>
      <h3>1) Buying by discount percentage instead of grind behavior</h3>
      <p>A deep sale can make a weak grinder look like a smart deal, especially in this price range. The problem is that discount math does not tell you whether the grinder can hold grind consistency across different brew methods. If a unit struggles with clumping, uneven particles, or wildly shifting output after small setting changes, the discounted price will not save your coffee routine. Prioritize known grind behavior first, then price.</p>

      <h3>2) Assuming all burr grinders are automatically espresso-ready</h3>
      <p>Many buyers hear “burr grinder” and assume any model can dial espresso shots reliably. In reality, some under-$200 grinders are clearly filter-first designs. They may reach fine settings, but step spacing is too broad to make repeatable espresso adjustments practical. If espresso is part of your plan, check adjustment design and user workflow details early instead of discovering this limitation after purchase.</p>

      <h3>3) Ignoring workflow friction (retention, static, cleanup)</h3>
      <p>Shoppers often focus on burr size and motor claims while ignoring daily usability. Retention and static are not minor annoyances. They affect flavor freshness, dose consistency, and whether you actually keep your station clean. A slightly less “impressive” grinder with cleaner grounds handling can outperform a spec-heavy alternative over months of real use because the routine stays smooth.</p>

      <h3>4) Overbuying complexity for a simple brew routine</h3>
      <p>If your household only brews batch drip coffee, an espresso-first single-dose workflow may be unnecessary complexity. Complex grinders are not bad; they are just optimized for different goals. Match features to your brewing habits. This keeps your learning curve reasonable and prevents paying for capabilities you rarely use.</p>

      <h3>5) Skipping maintenance planning</h3>
      <p>Even great grinders lose performance when burr chambers and chutes accumulate old grounds. A good buying decision includes a realistic cleaning cadence. If you cannot commit to quick weekly brushing and periodic deeper cleaning, choose a model with easy access and simpler disassembly. Consistent maintenance protects both flavor and long-term value more than chasing one extra settings notch on paper.</p>

      <h3>6) Expecting one grinder to solve recipe inconsistency alone</h3>
      <p>A better grinder improves your floor and ceiling, but it does not replace dose control, water ratio consistency, and brew-time discipline. Many buyers upgrade hardware and keep chaotic workflow habits, then conclude the grinder “did not make a difference.” Pair your grinder upgrade with stable brew ratios and incremental setting changes. That is how under-$200 equipment delivers genuinely better cups.</p>
