  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: how to choose the right burr coffee grinder under 200</h2>

      <h3>1) Start with brew method, not marketing labels</h3>
      <p>Before comparing specs, define your real routine. If you brew drip, pour over, or French press most days, prioritize consistency in medium and coarse ranges plus easy cleanup. If you make espresso regularly, adjustment precision matters more than hopper size or timer extras. Matching grinder design to brew style prevents most buyer regret in this category.</p>

      <h3>2) Understand adjustment systems before you buy</h3>
      <p>Stepped systems are easier to repeat and friendlier for new users, but large step spacing can limit espresso tuning. Stepless systems offer finer control but add complexity. Under $200, the best value often comes from grinders that keep workflow intuitive while still giving enough fine-range resolution to avoid major shot swings.</p>

      <h3>3) Evaluate retention and static as daily quality factors</h3>
      <p>Retention (old grounds trapped inside) and static (grounds spraying or clinging) directly affect cup freshness and kitchen friction. A grinder with excellent spec-sheet numbers but frustrating grounds handling can feel worse over time than a slightly less technical model with cleaner behavior. Prioritize machines you can keep tidy without a ritual.</p>

      <h3>4) Choose a budget tier with intent</h3>
      <p>In this segment, there are three practical tiers. Around $100 is strong for filter-first upgrades. Around $150 adds better all-around flexibility. Near $200 is where espresso-capable control improves meaningfully. Decide which tier aligns with your next 12 months of brewing, not just this weekend’s impulse purchase.</p>

      <h3>5) Build a repeatable maintenance cadence</h3>
      <p>Weekly brushing and monthly deeper cleaning preserve grind consistency and flavor clarity. If you need a routine, use this <a href="/posts/how-to-clean-burr-coffee-grinder.html">burr grinder cleaning guide</a>. Most “my grinder got worse” complaints come from retention buildup and neglected burr care rather than sudden hardware failure.</p>

      <h3>6) Use linked guides to improve results faster</h3>
      <p>A better grinder matters, but your recipe consistency matters just as much. Pair your purchase with this <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a> and this <a href="/posts/burr-grinder-settings-for-espresso.html">burr grinder settings guide for espresso</a>. Dialing workflow and dose discipline usually create bigger quality jumps than chasing one more feature tier.</p>
